data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's what breaks and the fixes:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func`, not `Expression<Func>`

Your expression-tree construction **won't compile** because the overload now accepts a plain lambda. Replace the entire block:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — no expression trees needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now auto-uniquified & nested paths changed

**Two sub-changes:**

- **Uniquification**: `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one column. Now EF appends a number (e.g. `Street`, `Street1`). This will generate a migration that **renames columns** and can break existing data.
- **Nested paths**: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` previously mapped to `BillingAddress_City`. Now it maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix** — pin the old column names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin the old name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

> **Important**: After upgrading, run `dotnet ef migrations add VerifyNoChanges` and inspect the migration. If it tries to rename columns, add `HasColumnName()` calls until the migration is empty.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging. Your code won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText (redacted) for logging instead of command.CommandText
    }
}
```

The same `logCommandText` parameter was added to `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, `CommandScalarExecuted`, `CommandNonQueryExecuting`, `CommandNonQueryExecuted`, and their async variants — update all of them.
